      <!-- ===== PART I — WHY AUSTRALIA ===== -->
      <section class="ch-part">
        <div class="ch-part-num">Part One</div>
        <h2 class="ch-h2">Why Australia.</h2>
        <p class="ch-deck-2">The case, in numbers and in lived experience.</p>
      </section>

      <p class="ch-body ch-dropcap">Australia is experiencing an unprecedented demand for medical professionals. Understanding what makes it attractive is the first step in your journey — and it is the question we will settle in this opening chapter before any document or exam is mentioned.</p>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">1. High demand for doctors</h3>
      <p class="ch-body">Australia's healthcare system is actively seeking qualified doctors, creating exceptional opportunities for IMGs ready to make the move.</p>

      <div class="ch-stat-grid">
        <div class="ch-stat">
          <div class="ch-stat-num">16,900<em>+</em></div>
          <div class="ch-stat-label">Vacant positions nationwide as of 2025 — across every specialty and region.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-stat">
          <div class="ch-stat-num">4</div>
          <div class="ch-stat-label">High-demand specialties: Emergency Medicine, General Practice, Psychiatry and Rural Medicine.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-stat">
          <div class="ch-stat-num">18<em>%</em></div>
          <div class="ch-stat-label">Regional signing bonuses, calculated as a share of annual salary.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-stat">
          <div class="ch-stat-num">28<em>d</em></div>
          <div class="ch-stat-label">Average visa processing time for healthcare workers under priority lanes.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>Structured training.</strong> Clear progression pathways with defined milestones.</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-department exposure.</strong> Opportunity to work across multiple departments as a junior doctor.</li>
        <li><strong>Strong mentorship.</strong> A culture of senior consultants guiding junior doctors.</li>
        <li><strong>Research opportunities.</strong> Conference funding support and academic research pathways.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">2. Financial benefits that matter</h3>
      <p class="ch-body">Salary comparison, 2025 data.</p>

      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>Junior doctor salary.</strong> AUD $89,000 – $110,000 annually.</li>
        <li><strong>Earning multiplier.</strong> 2.8× more than Indian counterparts, against an INR 15 lakh average.</li>
        <li><strong>Overtime pay.</strong> Time-and-a-half for hours beyond the contracted 38–40 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>Weekend loading.</strong> Additional 50–100% pay for weekend shifts.</li>
      </ul>

      <aside class="ch-callout">
        <div class="ch-callout-label">Real-world example</div>
        <p>"In my first year as an HMO in Queensland, I earned AUD $95,000 base salary plus AUD $18,000 in overtime. After taxes, I saved AUD $35,000 — more than my entire annual salary back home."</p>
        <div class="ch-callout-author">— Dr. Anika, Mumbai</div>
      </aside>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">3. The work-life balance revolution</h3>
      <p class="ch-body">Unlike many healthcare systems worldwide, Australia prioritises sustainable medical practice with strong protections for doctors.</p>

      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>38–40 hour week.</strong> The contracted workweek — not the 60–80 hours common elsewhere.</li>
        <li><strong>4 weeks annual leave.</strong> Mandatory to take. Rest is built into the system.</li>
        <li><strong>Professional development leave.</strong> 2 weeks paid leave annually for CPD and upskilling.</li>
        <li><strong>Sick leave.</strong> Generous allowances without penalty — your health comes first.</li>
        <li><strong>76% of IMGs report better quality of life</strong> compared to their home country.</li>
        <li><strong>World-class Medicare.</strong> Access to Australia's public healthcare system from day one.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">4. Straightforward immigration pathways</h3>
      <p class="ch-body">Australia offers one of the clearest paths to permanent residency for medical professionals — a structured progression from work visa to citizenship.</p>

      <ol class="ch-steps">
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">Skills in Demand Visa (Subclass 482)</div>
            <p>Initial work visa with employer sponsorship — your entry point.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">Permanent Residency (Subclass 190 / 189)</div>
            <p>Available after 2–3 years of work experience in Australia.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">Citizenship</div>
            <p>After 4 years total — including at least 1 year as a Permanent Resident.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>Priority processing.</strong> Healthcare workers average just 28 days for visa processing.</li>
        <li><strong>Age limit removed.</strong> No age ceiling for doctors under the Skills in Demand visa.</li>
        <li><strong>Family inclusion.</strong> Spouse can work; children can study in Australian schools.</li>
        <li><strong>Extended family options.</strong> A path to bringing parents on extended visitor visas.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- ===== PART II — THE CORE FRAMEWORK ===== -->
      <section class="ch-part">
        <div class="ch-part-num">Part Two</div>
        <h2 class="ch-h2">Understanding the three AMC pathways.</h2>
        <p class="ch-deck-2">Australia recognises three distinct routes for IMGs. The right one depends on where you trained, what you have already passed, and how senior you are.</p>
      </section>

      <aside class="ch-callout ch-callout-warn">
        <div class="ch-callout-label">Important</div>
        <p>Your pathway choice is effectively permanent once you begin the process. While you can switch pathways in exceptional circumstances, it involves additional costs and delays. Therefore, understanding each pathway thoroughly before committing is crucial for your success.</p>
      </aside>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Pathway 1 — Standard Pathway <span class="ch-h3-tag">Most common · 78% of IMGs</span></h3>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>Who it is for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li>MBBS / MD graduates who have completed an internship in their home country.</li>
        <li>Graduates from medical schools listed in the International Medical Education Directory (IMED).</li>
        <li>Those seeking general registration to practice as junior doctors.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>The two-step assessment:</strong></p>
      <ol class="ch-steps">
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">AMC CAT MCQ Examination</div>
            <p>150 multiple-choice questions over 3.5 hours. Computer-adaptive format covering Medicine, Surgery, O&amp;G, Pediatrics, Psychiatry, and Public Health. <strong>Current pass rate: 50%. Cost: AUD $2,920.</strong></p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">AMC Clinical Examination — or Workplace-Based Assessment</div>
            <p><strong>Clinical Exam:</strong> 16 assessed stations. Pass requirement: 9 / 14 stations (updated March 2024). Pass rate: 35%. Cost: AUD $3,991 in-person, AUD $4,391 online.</p>
            <p><strong>WBA alternative:</strong> 6–12 months supervised practice. 98% success rate. Cost: AUD $12,000. Waiting time: 6–18 months depending on location.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="ch-stat-grid ch-stat-grid-2">
        <div class="ch-stat">
          <div class="ch-stat-num">18 – 24</div>
          <div class="ch-stat-label">Months timeline — from start to first job offer.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-stat">
          <div class="ch-stat-num">$14 – 15<em>K</em></div>
          <div class="ch-stat-label">Total investment in AUD for the full Standard Pathway.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="ch-callout">
        <div class="ch-callout-label">Success story</div>
        <p>"I started my AMC journey during an internship in Delhi. Passed MCQ in 8 months, Clinical in 11. The new 9/14 pass requirement made a huge difference — I passed on my second attempt. Now working as an HMO in Brisbane, earning AUD $98,000."</p>
        <div class="ch-callout-author">— Dr. Priya, AIIMS graduate</div>
      </aside>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Pathway 2 — Competent Authority Pathway <span class="ch-h3-tag">Fast-track · 15% of IMGs</span></h3>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>Who it is for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li>Medical graduates who have completed recognised examinations in the UK, Ireland, USA, Canada, or New Zealand.</li>
        <li>Those with 1–2 years of supervised work experience in these countries.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>Qualifying examinations by country:</strong></p>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>UK / Ireland.</strong> PLAB 1 &amp; 2 plus 1 year supervised practice.</li>
        <li><strong>USA.</strong> USMLE Steps 1, 2 &amp; 3 plus 2 years supervised practice.</li>
        <li><strong>Canada.</strong> MCCQE plus 1 year supervised practice.</li>
        <li><strong>New Zealand.</strong> NZREX plus 1 year supervised practice.</li>
      </ul>

      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>Bypass AMC examinations entirely.</strong> Direct pathway to general registration — no MCQ or Clinical Exam required.</li>
        <li><strong>Faster processing.</strong> 12–18 months versus 18–24 for the Standard Pathway.</li>
        <li><strong>Lower costs.</strong> AUD $8,000 – $10,000 versus $14,000 – $15,000 for Standard.</li>
      </ul>

      <aside class="ch-callout ch-callout-good">
        <div class="ch-callout-label">2025 fast-track update</div>
        <p>New expedited processing for PLAB / USMLE holders with 2+ years experience — registration now possible in just 6 months.</p>
      </aside>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Pathway 3 — Specialist Pathway (SIMG) <span class="ch-h3-tag">Advanced · 7% of IMGs</span></h3>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>Who it is for:</strong></p>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li>Specialists with 4+ years post-graduation experience.</li>
        <li>Those seeking specialist recognition or area-of-need positions.</li>
        <li>Consultants wanting to practice at specialist level in Australia.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>The assessment process:</strong></p>
      <ol class="ch-steps">
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">College Assessment</div>
            <p>Evaluation by the relevant Australian specialist college — RACP, ACEM, RANZCOG and so on.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">Documentation Review</div>
            <p>Detailed logbook of procedures, supervision records and teaching experience.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="ch-step-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="ch-step-h">Potential Supervised Practice</div>
            <p>6–24 months depending on the college's assessment outcome.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="ch-body"><strong>2025 expedited options — priority specialties:</strong></p>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>Anaesthesia and Pain Medicine.</strong> 6-month assessment timeline.</li>
        <li><strong>Psychiatry.</strong> Fast-track for rural positions.</li>
        <li><strong>Emergency Medicine.</strong> Priority for regional hospitals.</li>
        <li><strong>Rural General Practice.</strong> Accelerated pathway for rural areas.</li>
      </ul>

