      <!-- ===== PART IV — MYTHS DEBUNKED ===== -->
      <section class="ch-part">
        <div class="ch-part-num">Part Four</div>
        <h2 class="ch-h2">Common myths, debunked.</h2>
      </section>

      <div class="ch-myths">
        <div class="ch-myth">
          <div class="ch-myth-num">Myth 1</div>
          <div class="ch-myth-claim">"Australia doesn't recognise Indian medical degrees."</div>
          <p><strong>Reality.</strong> Indian degrees from MCI / NMC-recognised institutions are fully accepted. Over 12,000 Indian doctors currently practice in Australia. The key is proper documentation through EPIC verification.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-myth">
          <div class="ch-myth-num">Myth 2</div>
          <div class="ch-myth-claim">"You need Australian clinical experience to get hired."</div>
          <p><strong>Reality.</strong> Many hospitals hire IMGs directly after AMC MCQ + English test for limited registration positions. Australian clinical experience helps but is not mandatory for first jobs.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-myth">
          <div class="ch-myth-num">Myth 3</div>
          <div class="ch-myth-claim">"Regional jobs mean isolation and poor facilities."</div>
          <p><strong>Reality.</strong> Regional centres like Geelong (1 hour from Melbourne) or Newcastle (2 hours from Sydney) offer excellent facilities, shorter commutes and stronger community support.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-myth">
          <div class="ch-myth-num">Myth 4</div>
          <div class="ch-myth-claim">"AMC exams are impossible to pass."</div>
          <p><strong>Reality.</strong> With proper preparation, success is achievable. AMC MCQ has a 50% pass rate, AMC Clinical 35%, and WBA has a 98% success rate for those who can access it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ch-myth">
          <div class="ch-myth-num">Myth 5</div>
          <div class="ch-myth-claim">"Australia is too expensive for junior doctors."</div>
          <p><strong>Reality.</strong> While living costs are high, junior doctor salaries are proportionally higher. Most IMGs save AUD $25,000 – $35,000 annually even after all expenses.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== PART V — ACTION PLAN ===== -->
      <section class="ch-part">
        <div class="ch-part-num">Part Five</div>
        <h2 class="ch-h2">Your first 90 days.</h2>
        <p class="ch-deck-2">A clear, structured plan for your first three months — to build the strongest possible foundation for your Australian medical journey.</p>
      </section>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Weeks 1–2 · Foundation setup</h3>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li>Create EPIC account at ecfmg.org/epic.</li>
        <li>Gather required documents: academic transcript, internship completion certificate with exact dates, medical degree.</li>
        <li>Set up finances — ensure access to a credit card for international payments.</li>
        <li><em>Tip.</em> Use original degree certificate — provisional certificates are rejected in 23% of cases.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Weeks 3–4 · Registration and planning</h3>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li>Submit EPIC verification — processing time is 2–3 business days.</li>
        <li>Create AMC portfolio using your EPIC ID.</li>
        <li>Choose your English test — PTE is recommended for being cheaper and having higher pass rates.</li>
        <li>Join IMG communities: the "Indian Doctors in Australia" Facebook group has over 45,000 members.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Months 2–3 · Preparation and strategy</h3>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li>Book the AMC MCQ exam — aim for 6–8 months of preparation.</li>
        <li>Start English test preparation after AMC MCQ for optimal timing.</li>
        <li>Research target locations — identify preferred states and hospitals.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="ch-h3">Preparation resources</h3>
      <ul class="ch-bullets">
        <li><strong>Free.</strong> AMC Handbook and the official AMC website practice questions.</li>
        <li><strong>Paid.</strong> AMCQBank ($899 / 6 months), PassMedicine Australia ($650 / year).</li>
      </ul>

